{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17535578","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17535578"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:57:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:57:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15490"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15490","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15490"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.11,0.55,0.09,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8181"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89879"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8181","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8181"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15490"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74048"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"108"},{"type":"tags","id":"4972"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19810"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30612"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89879","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/89879"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman who works as a junior doctor presents to the Staff Health clinic after being notified of potential exposure to tuberculosis. Three weeks ago, she assisted in a bronchoscopy on a patient who has now been confirmed to have pulmonary tuberculosis. She wore standard surgical mask and gloves during the 45-minute procedure. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She received the Bacillus Calmette-Gu\u00e9rin (BCG) vaccine as an infant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. She has no respiratory symptoms and her chest examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Mantoux test","Commence isoniazid prophylaxis","Interferon gamma release assay now and in 8-10 weeks","Sputum acid-fast bacilli microscopy","Chest X-ray"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a significant occupational exposure to \u003Cem\u003EMycobacterium tuberculosis\u003C/em\u003E during an aerosol-generating procedure. The healthcare worker was not wearing appropriate personal protective equipment (N95/P2 mask) at the time of exposure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBoth \u003Cstrong\u003EMantoux test\u003C/strong\u003E (tuberculin skin test, TST) and \u003Cstrong\u003Einterferon gamma release assay\u003C/strong\u003E (IGRA) are acceptable tests for contact tracing in adults exposed to active tuberculosis. However, IGRA is preferred in this case due to the patient\u0027s history of BCG vaccination. Initial testing establishes a baseline, while repeat testing at 8-10 weeks can detect conversion indicating recent infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChest X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if the healthcare worker had symptoms suggestive of active tuberculosis or if IGRA testing was positive, but it is not the first-line investigation for asymptomatic exposure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIsoniazid prophylaxis\u003C/strong\u003E would only be indicated if there was evidence of recent conversion on IGRA testing or other high-risk factors. Prophylactic treatment carries risks and should not be initiated without evidence of infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESputum acid-fast bacilli microscopy\u003C/strong\u003E would only be appropriate if the healthcare worker had symptoms suggestive of active pulmonary tuberculosis, such as productive cough, which is not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis case also highlights the importance of appropriate personal protective equipment during high-risk procedures. A surgical mask does not provide adequate protection against tuberculosis; an N95/P2 mask should have been worn during the bronchoscopy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Either tuberculin skin test or interferon gamma release assay can be used for tuberculosis contact tracing in adults.","IGRA is preferred for BCG-vaccinated individuals, particularly those with multiple BCG doses or vaccination after age one.","Personal protective equipment including N95/P2 masks is essential when caring for patients with suspected pulmonary tuberculosis."],"references":["Updated Guidelines for Using Interferon Gamma Release Assays to Detect Mycobacterium tuberculosis Infection --- United States, 2010 [Internet]. www.cdc.gov. Available from: https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/rr5905a1.htm\u200c","Position statement on interferon-\u03b3 release assays for the detection of latent tuberculosis infection: Contact investigation in adults. The Department of Health and Aged Care. https://www1.health.gov.au/internet/main/publishing.nsf/Content/cdi4104-c#6"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74048"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15490"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74048","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74048"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-11T13:34:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-11T13:34:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8181"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questio